values:
Valentine's Day marked the beginning of our short study tour. A couple of the girls made brownies and brought them to the bus for a special v-day gift to everyone. We took a bus from Copenhagen out towards Fyn. This island is one of the three major islands. Denmark is made of a large collection of islands. How many? I'm sure I will know by the end of the day (403 is the answer).

      Connecting Zealand and Fyn is the 2nd largest suspension bridge in the world. Until recently, it was the largest. From Fyn, we drove to Jylland. The connection between Fyn and Jylland actually has 2 bridges. They built the 2nd, and now main bridge soon after the first because traffic was too heavy for the first and smaller bridge. We got to stop and take smaple at Romo, which is essentially a large mudflat.

      There were several different bivalves there, but a very small oxic layer, maybe 4 to 5cm. One of the irls in my group we were sampling with got stuck in the mud and fell over (Leila). After the sampling we headed for Kolding Hus. We were suppose to have a guided tour, but driving times were longer than anticipated and the guide left befre we got there. We had called and told them we were 30min away. So we got to explore for ourselves for 45min. It was interesting with the silver, toy, and other exhibitions, it would have been better with a guide.

      We finished the day by checking into our hostel, excellent one called Ribe Byferie, and had dinner/sample identification. Dinner was basically meat and potatoes with brown sauce that is traditional to Denmark. At the hostel I'm staying with six other people: Kim, Cassie, Leila, Brianna, Heidi, and Lauren. My collection group consists of Hogni, Kim, Brianna, Leila, and myself. Identification for the mudflats turned up snails, bivalves, and worms. I went back to the hostel and slept, but some people went out this night.

      Friday the 15th included a trip to Blavand Huk. This beach had sand both course and fine. There were a lot of different species, but we didn't get to sample anything living because we weren't far enough out to sea. This lace had the same basic salinity as the mud flats but a much deeper anoxic level. One thing interesting to note was the fact the mudflats had a higher organic content than the beach because of the low turbity which means organic matter can settle to the bottom.

      We went to lunch by the water after sampling. I had a tasty chicken and pasta dish with a mix of vegetables. Most people had dishes of fish because it was basically a fish and chips restaurant. We went to the Ribe Viking Museum after this and learned a little history about the town. We also got a small walking tour and learned that if the courtyard gates are open, you're allowed to go in for a look. We had dinner at the same restaurant as before that included ground pork patties with onions and more brown sauce. After, a group of us went out. By midnight everyone was out at this bar/dance club.

      It was very smokey. Besides that, it was a good time. I got a free Galliano shot after asking a couple of Danes what they were. It was really good. It is Galliano liquor on the bottom with whipped cream and coffee on top. On Wednesday night I also went out. It was a martini social with a Danish club called So Sophisticated. I had a raspberry martini and a drink called the Chocolate Chicorita. It was amazing, basically an alcoholic blanded banana split.

      One other small detail about Friday night wth the girls, I teamed up with Cassie and played Kim and Miranda at pool. We won! That in itself was fun. I also had a Danish girl asking me to shoot pool balls for her because she was losing to some guy. Today wil include more smapling on the way back to Copenhagen and hopefully a little more sleep.

I have been really busy with classes and work lately. I have a couple different research papers that I'm working on. There is a field study coming up this weekend that I'm really looking forward to. We're going to Jutland and making a couple stops to sample mairing organisms. It'll be intersting. Besides myself and the person I met up with for dinner last night had a great time talking scientifically to someone that studies a completely different topic and didn't like fish.

      And on the subject of dinner... I went with this guy named Kyle to a place called Sakura. It was a nice little Japanese restaurant. It was chosen because Kyle saw an advertisement for it and when I brought up Meso Soup at the MEB dinner, it came up. He's a vegetarian and thus we were talking about tofu. But it was amazingly good. I had an assorted plate of 6 different pieces and a bowl of meso soup. I have recently found out I really like a whole bunch of different foods.

      One thing I find particularly interesting is the fact that certain foods I don't like by itself, I do like blended with some other flavor. Take for example my dislikes of egg yolks and rye bread. They have this dark rye bread called 'ruple' (or at least that is how it is pronounced) and it's a kind of hard, dry bread. I find it tastes best with a sliced hard boiled egg, yes yolk and white. Magnifique! Other than that, I liked every slice of sushi that was on my plate, including the imatation crab and avocado roll (and I detest imatation crab!).

      At the moment, I've got a trip to Berlin the weekend after next planned and an outline for spring break. Myself and a girl named Yuri are going to fly to Prague and take a train to Budapest, Vienna, Venice, Berne, and finally Munich then fly out from there. It is going to be amazing and hopefully will contain a day trip for snowboarding on Switzerland's side of the Alps! What an experience that would be. Hopefully I'll be able to extend my trip so that I can experience France at the end of my study abroad experience.

      And I almost forgot to mention the new navel ring I bought on Friday. It is a scorpion shape that has the tail sticking through the peircing. Yeah, kinda a weird thing to be excited about, I know. So now it is back to reading/researching for my classes.

Tuesday was the start of my 5th class: Energy and Element Cycling. We were late due to the tight train schedule. At least we won't have the same issue on Friday. The class is really interesting and based on a topic I will be doing a research paper on. At least I know I'm interested in the topic!

      The last weekend was, for the most part, uneventful except for a walk near the Roskilde Fjord and the Superbowl. It was a really nice walk and helped give me ideas on my research paper. I'll be studying Oxygen Depletion in the Danish Fjords. I also got to see a small sampling of the wildlife that is out there. Lots of muscles and clams. I find it so interesting to see the things you are studying. The Globe is the bar I went to for the superbowl. I only stayed there for the first quarter and part of the second. I decided that getting home to sleep and being able to go to class the next day was a little more important. And I still didn't get home until 3AM!

      Wednesday we had a trip to a mosque. That, in itself was interesting. I got the question I have been wanting to ask for a week answered. I didn't know if the teacher would know the answer becuse it is kind of personal to the Muslim religion, so it was nice getting their prespective on it.

      I am currently working on a research paper for Marine Biology as well as planning for Spring Break and maybe some weekend trips. It's really different being able to go to another country for the weekend and have enough time to explore. I'm loving it.

I never ended up going clubbing last week, but maybe this week. Not really sure if I'll be able to stay up late or not. So far I've had 4 of my 5 classes. It is going to be challenging, but I will survive. The classes are similar to back home, but the teachers speak relatively good english.

      Last Monday I found my way out to Valby Hallen. It was easier than I expected, but also took longer. THis place is a gymnasium and had a lot of different things going on. The reason I was there was for Ultimate. Before this night, I had never really played organized Ultimate. It was a blast!

      We had drills of all different types and some practice in play postions. In the end we played a full game. One of the gream things about this team was that it was all girls! I have never seen so many come out for frisbee. I'll have to go back again.

      On Wednesday we went beer tasting. We were at the Carlsberg/Jacobsen Brewhouse. We had a tour and in the end some beer tasting. The tour was great. We got to see the whole history behind the company and a small portion of the micro-brewery. Near the bar, they had a smelling station so that you could figure out which beer you would prefer.

      I started out trying the Jacobsen Brown Ale. From all the ones I tasted, I think this one was the best. But I think we (our group of 10) ended up trying all the beers they offered. There was a thick, dark beer that we swore tasted like coke and coffee. It was very syrup-like. A couple you could really taste some of the smells. I'm not a big fan of the "rose" flavor, but don't mind the honey. The woody/oak or clove ones are pretty good too.

      After the day at the brewery, I went to my host dad's mother's house. It was her birthday, so I got to celebrate with them. I was expecting more singing. We did have a traditional birthday cake though. It's like a layer cake with cake, custard, and some type of defrosted fruit with sugar in it. Whipped cream was used as frosting. It was delicious. There was also rolls and these pancake textured dough (cooked) balls. I had one of both. It was a very tasteful day of nw experiences. No one at the birthday party spoke english but the people I'm living with, but everyone was really nice to me. Danes are awesome!

Classes start on the 24th and so far so good. I think my Muslims class is going to be really hard, but I'll just have to work at it. I found out that my Energy and Element Cycling course has another study tour associated with it, which should be fun. Unfortunently it means I probably can't go on the Bike tour. I guess that just means I'll definently go on he Sweden canoe trip.

      Yesterday was out cafe trip. We went to a rather small place: Cafe Theodors. It was very nice, they were even showing the handball game; Denmark won! We did a little walking tour, but because it was dark, we didn't really see much. I had this great Curry Chicken sandwich with Mango sauce. Not bad for my first meal out.

      Tonight was the DIS welcome party. It took place at Luux, a very upscale club. DIS even gave everyone one free drink. Being me however, I bought myself something. He (the Bartender) said it was a smooth margarita and it mostly consisted of ice, vodka, and mint. It was my first legal drink! It cost quite a bit but I made up for it when one of my friends bought my free drink card for about half what my drink cost. It was a blast. I must say it was the most fun I've had going out since the summer; I need to hit up the town a couple weekends while I'm here.

      I also met several of the other IU students, including the one other non-business student. It's fun to have something in common with people. Sadly, my host family was waiting up or me, plus having things to do on Saturday I had to leave earlier than I would ahve liked. But there will be more outtings in the future, so I don't need to worry about one night. And oh, watch your drinks!

Over the last two days we learned a little Danish. Unfortunently I haven't really been able to utilize it. Although, I can understand more of it than I use to.

I was able to visit a ouple of parks near DIS on Wednesday with a girl named Leila (?). She is in the Marine and Evniornmental Biology (MEB) program with me. The parks are beautiful! There is a botanical garden and greenhouse at Botanisk Have, a 10min walk from DIS! Across the street is Rosenborg castle. All I wanted since the bus tour was to get a picture of it and I finally did! It's just too bad there is so much construction going on. Then again you have to do a lot of work to keep a town as old as Copenhagen looking in good, usable shape. On the 22nd I walked through Orsteds Parken; I'll ave to go back when it's light out.

I finally bought myself a pair of heels! They are black and white plaid print with closed rounded toes and probably 3 inches tall. They also have a small bow on the front. What happened was I walked pass the store and they were in the window, I said "oh! I really like those" but I kept walking. Next day I did the same exact thing, but this time I went in and tried them on. I now know I wear a 38 in shoes out here. So, I went shoe shopping comparing prices and styles at other stores. IN the end I came back and bought them for 200kr! (About $40). They were 50% off.

I have also decided to go on the Bornholm bike trp and trying to decide if I should go on the Sweden canoe trip. I am not going skiing the French Alps for a week, but I am planing a train trip around Europe. My host family is wonderful! They are even giving my tips as to where to go, how long to stay, and how long it will take me to get there. I am so excited! I might not get to see evertyhing I want in 2 weeks, but depending on what happens with my summer plans, I msy extend my trip and go see what I missed. More updates on the trip to come!

Orientation started on Sunday. Basically we drove a half an hour so that I could pick up mone and a bag of paperwork for the next few days. That night we went to Simone's concert. I was disappointed by the lack of French horns and the sound that lack there of created. The music was good for some of it, but overall it seemed as if the music was too hard for the students at the time.

Yesterday we had an intro to DIS at the black diamond. Named because the black building had a diamond-like cut shape. After this we got to take a bus/walking tour of Copenhagen. It was fun and all, but if I get lost in the city, I'll still have no idea where I am. We did see the "little mermaid" which is a statue of human size. Everyone thought it would be bigger. Other highlights included a hallocaust museum, the library of congress, several castles, and the royal mansions.

In the evening, I went to a meeting about sports. If there is a club closer to Roskilde that teaches handball, I will definently join. I hope to get on an Ultimate team as well. Both are offered through the USG program, but that takes place in Amager (over 35km away!). But I'll probably do it anyway.

Today we hae an introduction to the DIS building itself and all it's features. It's at some other random building that I have no idea how I'm going to  find, but I need to be there at 9. Other than that we have a "Surviving Danish" class that is an intensive 3 hours of Danish. Yikes! I hope I learn something.

I'm starting to sleep better, must mean I'm starting to get over my jet lag. Later today I will go to my first orientation meeting for DIS. I don't understand why I can't go earlier, but oh well.

Yesterday was my first Saturday with the family. Simone is acutally on a trip to Western Denmark (I think), so it was just Birgette and Johnny and myself. I did a Kakuro puzzle from the papaer and finish it. Later in the day, about midday, we went out shopping.

It was funny; we parked at a shell station and walked over to the mall. It was quite big. Two levels with a gym and cinema upstairs and a ton of shops downstairs. They and doing construction to add more shops.

There were 2 actors there as well doing advertising for one of the shops. WE went to a store like Walmart (as in it had a little of everything) but they didn't have what we needed. So we went to the downtown one behind the train station. I think it was called Korex (it's actually Forex), and I'm still not sure how to pronounce it.

I need to not take naps in the middle of the afternoon. I ended up doing that again. It's valuable time lost, but I guess I have today to make up fr it. Simone has a concert that I will be going to this evening, so I'd best be awake for that. I'm so excited that I'll finally be starting in on my schooling. I realy need to have something to do with myself.

On the 18th myself and 2 guys from the DIS program met up and took at day trip to Sweden. We went to a town called Malmo and walked around for several hours. There was the building called the "Twisted Torso" in which the top of the building was 90 degrees off from the bottom.

It was a good day except when I lost my return train ticket and had to buy a new one and then got off on the wrong train stop and got lost. I met a really nice man who helped me back to the train station. This also means I saw part of Copenhagen I would not have ordinarily seen. Thanks to my host mom, I didn't have to try and find my way back to Roskilde on my own. Next time I should bring my map.

The flight to Denmark was long, 11 hours and of that I only got 30min of sleep. I did get a bit more on the flight to Copenhagen. Last night I slpt alright but not as good as I could have. Unfortunently I can't seem to sleep at the moment, so I decided to put in my first study abroad entry.

My first afternoon in town was spent unpacking and hanging out with the new family: Birgette, Johnny, and Simone. We ha a nice meal including meat, bread, veggies, and dressing put together kind of like a sandwich. Yesterday included a trip into town, grocery shopping, a nap, and lasange. Now I'm regretting the nap, but what can you do? My host mother Birgette is really nice. She wants to make me feel at home. I would prefer she would ust do what she would normally do because I am intersted in what normal life is like. I keep saying this, but of course they still try to suit me.

Tomorrow should be fun. I'm meeting up with a couple other DIS student an we're going to take a train to Sweden. I'm looking forward to meeting them and going on my first Europe exploration. I hope I'll make some good friends that want to travel before Spring Break so that I won't be alone on my adventures. I found out I could get a Eurail pass for cheaper than any flights, but that it isn't going to Great Britian. Maybe I'll just check out the other 20 countries instead. Who knows?
